How the analyzer matches patterns:
- `java.referenced` ANNOTATION: import + apply annotation to class/method/field
- `java.referenced` IMPORT: import statement alone is sufficient
- `java.referenced` TYPE: use the FULLY QUALIFIED type name inline (e.g., `sun.misc.Unsafe obj = null;`). Do NOT rely on an import + short name â€” the analyzer needs the FQN in the code to resolve internal/encapsulated types.
- `java.referenced` METHOD_CALL: call using the FULLY QUALIFIED form (e.g., `org.junit.Assert.assertEquals(...)`). Do NOT use static imports â€” `import static org.junit.Assert.assertEquals` then `assertEquals(...)` will NOT match because the analyzer cannot resolve the FQN from a static import.
- `java.referenced` CONSTRUCTOR_CALL: use `new` with the fully qualified class name
- `java.referenced` IMPLEMENTS_TYPE: implement the interface
- `java.referenced` INHERITANCE: extend the class
- `java.dependency`: dependency in pom.xml with correct groupId:artifactId (name uses "groupId.artifactId" format)
- `builtin.xml`: pom.xml must contain the XML elements that the XPath expression matches (e.g., `<parent>`, `<plugin>` with the specified groupId/artifactId). Include the full XML structure in the pom.xml.
- `go.referenced`: import and reference the package
- `nodejs.referenced`: import the module/symbol
- `csharp.referenced`: use the namespace/type
- `builtin.filecontent`: include text matching the regex pattern

